h-century phenomenology. The heat of Beowulf reexamines the scholarship on Old English poetics from the mid-twentieth century as it intersected with post-war avant-garde poetics, and how understanding these critical histories can reshape how we read Beowulf now.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAesthetics in literature. 4aLiterature Studies 2022. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aAesthetics.  aBeowulf.  aContemporary poetry.  aEcopoetics.  aJack Spicer.  aOld English.  aPhenomenology.  aPoetics.  aRobin Blaser.  aTranslation.1 aRemein, Daniel C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2022 eBook-Packagez978311128144540uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152615059240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526150592423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526150592/original  a978-3-11-128144-5  Manchester University Press 2022 eBook-Packageb2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles